trial_type.Description: Comprenhesive information of stimulus and responses corresponding to each event

Levels.famous_second_early: Immediate repeated  presentation of famous face
Levels.famous_second_late: Delayed repeated  presentation of famous face
Levels.scrambled_second_early: Immediate repeated  presentation of scrambled face
Levels.scrambled_second_late: Delayed repeated  presentation of scrambled face
Levels.unfamiliar_second_early: Immediate repeated  presentation of unfamiliar face
Levels.unfamiliar_second_late: Delayed repeated  presentation of unfamiliar face
Levels.right_nonsym: Right button press to indicated less symmetric face
Levels.left_sym: Left button press to indicated more symmetric face
Levels.left_nonsym: Left button press to indicated less symmetric face
Levels.right_sym: Right button press to indicated more symmetric face
Levels.boundary: The boundary mark of each run as the run data was merged

event_type.Description: Represent the two more general types events in the experiment

Levels.button_press: Button pressing indicating level of symmetry of face presented

Levels.6: Immediate repeated  presentation of famous face
Levels.7: Delayed repeated  presentation of famous face
Levels.14: Immediate repeated  presentation of unfamiliar face
Levels.15: Delayed repeated  presentation of unfamiliar face
Levels.18: Immediate repeated  presentation of scrambled face
Levels.19: Delayed repeated  presentation of scrambled face

event_order.Description: Each image is presented twice. This index represent the order of presentation of each image

Levels.0: Not an image. This may be a button press or a boundary

trial_dist.Description: Distance in trial units since the previous presentation of the same image

time_dist.Description: Time since the previous presentation of the same image

README:
Multi-subject, multi-modal (sMRI+EEG) neuroimaging dataset
on face processing. Original data described at https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata20151
This is repackaged version of the EEG data in EEGLAB format. The data has gone through
minimal preprocessing including (see wh_extracteeg_BIDS.m):
- Ignoring fMRI and MEG data (sMRI preserved for EEG source localization)
- Extracting EEG channels out of the MEG/EEG fif data
- Adding fiducials
- Renaming EOG and EKG channels
- Extracting events from event channel
- Removing spurious events 5, 6, 7, 13, 14, 15, 17, 18 and 19
- Removing spurious event 24 for subject 3 run 4
- Renaming events taking into account button assigned to each subject
- Correcting event latencies (events have a shift of 34 ms)
- Resampling data to 250 Hz (this is a step that is done because
  this dataset is used as tutorial for EEGLAB and need to be lightweight)
- Merging run 1 to 6
- Removing event fields urevent and duration 
- Filling up empty fields for events boundary and stim_file.
- Saving as EEGLAB .set format

Ramon Martinez, Dung Truong, Scott Makeig, Arnaud Delorme (UCSD, La Jolla, CA, USA)

sub-002_task-FaceRecognition_eeg.json.TaskDescription: Subjects viewed stimuli on a screen during six, 7.5 minute runs. The stimuli were photographs of either a famous face (known to most of British or a scrambled face, and appeared for a random duration between 800 and 1,000 ms. Subjects were instructed to fixate centrally throughout the experiment. To ensure attention to each stimulus, participants were asked to press one of two keys with either their left or right index finger (assignment counter-balanced across participants). Their key-press was based on how symmetric they regarded each image: pressing one or the other key depending whether they thought the image was 'more' or 'less symmetric' than average.
